                  <summary>
                     <seg part="N" type="para">Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 486 is a small
                                codex that was copied around 1200, and which contains a
                                    <title>Miscellany of Greek religious texts</title>, including:
                                an excerpt of the Ecclesiasticus, a short section on the iambic
                                metre, doctrinal responses by Gregory of Nyssa (c. 330-c. 395),
                                Dionysius of Alexandria (d. c. 264), Nicon, and Peter, patriarch of
                                Antioch and other unedited texts. Delle Donne (2014) pointed out
                                that some texts in the manuscript have close links with other
                                miscellanies or belong to textual traditions whose origin and
                                circulation is located in southern Italy.</seg>
                     <seg part="N" type="para">The manuscript retains its original medieval binding.
                                As a result of the fragility of this binding it has only been
                                possible to image the exterior and interior of the covers and ff.
                                1r-9r.</seg>
                     <seg part="N" type="para">Dr Matteo Di Franco</seg>
                  </summary>
